> I think it might be important here that the registry urls differ only in the last path segment.
> 
> The `.docker/config.json` contains two entries
> 
> ```json
> {
>   "auths": {
>     "some-docker-registry.com/source-registry": {
>     },
>     "some-docker-registry.com/dest-registry": {
>     }
>   }
> }
> ```

I don’t think that’s ever been valid; only the host name part is considered, even if the URL syntax is used. Compare https://github.com/moby/moby/blob/3152f9436292115c97b4d8bb18c66cf97876ee75/registry/auth.go#L228 .

---

It’s honestly surprising to me that a single physical user (= single subject) should use different credentials for two repositories on a single registry (= single user account system and presumably administration domain). Is it something that happens frequently, for a _good_ reason? If so, adding `--src-authfile` and `--dest-authfile` would be warranted, sure, but it looks strange.

>  You could use the `--dest-creds` option in the `skopeo copy` command line and get it to work that way for now at least. 

@TomSweeneyRedHat I would like to avoid this, since I don't want to leak secrets on the command line (logs, process table). I currently have a different workaround, since one can access the registry by external dns, such as some-docker-registry.com and by service dns form inside OpenShift, such as docker-registry.default.svc:5000. This setup has two different hosts and hence is a workaround. 

@mtrmac my use case is copying images between different namespaces in OpenShift. By default an OpenShift cluster has one registry with repositories for each namespace. Access to the repositories is controlled by the `system:image-puller` and `system:image-pusher` role in each namespace. So in OpenShift it's standard behavior that different auths are required. I am not so familiar with registry access control on other Kubernetes clusters, but the setup and use case seem to make sense to me.
